elements.content: A series of nine complexes has been obtained from the hydrothermal reaction of uranyl nitrate with long-chain alkyldicarboxylic acids (HOOC-(CH2) n–2-COOH, denoted H2Cn) in the presence of cucurbit[6]uril (CB6), dimethylformamide (DMF), which generates dimethylammonium cations in situ, and additional alkaline-earth metal ions in some cases. The crystal structures of the three complexes [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(OH)2(C8)2(CB6)]·8H2O (1), [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(OH)2(C9)2(CB6)]·5H2O (2), and [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(OH)2(C9)2(CB6)]·8H2O (3) are closely related, since all contain the same tetranuclear motif held by two μ3-oxo and two μ2-hydroxo ions, and attached to CB6 by uranyl-O-carbonyl bonds. Two-dimensional assemblies are formed in 1 and 2 and a three-dimensional framework in 3. The cucurbituril molecule is not coordinated in compounds 4–9 but is present as a structure-directing agent. The complex [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(C6)3]·CB8·8H2O (4), in which cucurbit[8]uril (CB8) comes from the initial CB6, displays a stacking of planar uranyl–organic two-dimensional layers with sheets of CB8 molecules. An analogous overall arrangement involving one-dimensional ribbons based on a uranyl trinuclear motif is found in the complex [H2NMe2][(UO2)3O(OH)2(C7)(HC7)(H2O)0.5]·CB6·4H2O (5). A helicoidal one-dimensional polymer is formed in [H2NMe2]4[(UO2)4(C10)6]·CB6·H2O (6), in which the packing is quite intricate. Finally, the last three complexes, [Ca2(CB6)(H2O)7(DMF)][(UO2)8O4(C8)6(H2O)]·6H2O (7), [Sr2(CB6)(H2O)7(DMF)3][(UO2)6O2(C8)6]·2H2O (8), and [Sr2(CB6)(H2O)8(DMF)2][(UO2)8O4(C10)6] (9), include columns built from alkaline-earth ion complexes with CB6, which are either molecular (7) or one-dimensional polymeric (8 and 9). In complexes 7 and 9, these columns are separated from one another and surrounded by the corrugated two-dimensional uranyl–organic assemblies, while, in 8, the latter are planar grids whose stacking defines channels in which the columns are nestled. These results provide new examples of the potential of cucurbiturils as uranyl complexants or as structure-directing agents. The sheets or columns readily formed by CBs, either free or complexed, appear as particularly well suited to associate with the two-dimensional or ribbon-like topologies most common among uranyl–organic species, which opens perspectives for the design of hybrid layered materials.

Among the simplest of these ligands are the linear, aliphatic dicarboxylates of the general formula [OOC-(CH2) n–2-COO]2–, denoted Cn in the following. The coordination polymers formed by uranyl ions with the shortest members, malonate (C3), succinate (C4), and glutarate (C5) have been frequently investigated, while those of the larger ones, adipate (C6), pimelate (C7), suberate (C8), azelate (C9), and sebacate (C10), have been thoroughly studied by Cahill’s group, comparison being made with lanthanide ion complexes. In the latter cases, one- to three-dimensional uranyl–organic assemblies were isolated, and the effect of additional bipyridine molecules, which can assume the different roles of ligand or structure-directing species, was also examined. More recently, during an investigation of cucurbit[n]urils with n = 5–8 (Scheme ; denoted CBn hereafter) as ligands for uranyl ions, the use of such dicarboxylic acids to get rotaxane-like compounds analogous to those comprising alkyldiammonium cations was attempted. Introduction

Uranyl-organic assemblies have been the subject of numerous studies in the past few years, with a particular emphasis on their original architectures, which result from the peculiar geometric requirements of the linear uranyl cation. Carboxylates and polycarboxylates are particularly well suited for uranyl complexation, and they are very commonly used in this field. Among the simplest of these ligands are the linear, aliphatic dicarboxylates of the general formula [OOC-(CH2) n-2-COO]2-, denoted Cn in the following. The coordination polymers formed by uranyl ions with the shortest members, malonate (C3), succinate (C4), and glutarate (C5) have been frequently investigated, while those of the larger ones, adipate (C6), pimelate (C7), suberate (C8), azelate (C9), and sebacate (C10), have been thoroughly studied by Cahill's group, comparison being made with lanthanide ion complexes. In the latter cases, one- to three-dimensional uranyl-organic assemblies were isolated, and the effect of additional bipyridine molecules, which can assume the different roles of ligand or structure-directing species, was also examined. More recently, during an investigation of cucurbit[n]urils with n = 5-8 (Scheme ; denoted CBn hereafter) as ligands for uranyl ions, the use of such dicarboxylic acids to get rotaxane-like compounds analogous to those comprising alkyldiammonium cations was attempted. However, although a pseudorotaxane involving uncomplexed azelaic acid was indeed observed, the only uranyl complex which could be isolated was a compound uniting two independent dinuclear complexes, one with CB6 and the other with sebacate, with no coordination polymer being generated in this case. In the present work, it has been found that a modification of the experimental procedure provides a series of uranyl complexes with CB6 and either C7, C8, C9, or C10, some of them containing also alkaline-earth ions, in which the dicarboxylate ligands give rise to polymeric assemblies, the CB6 molecule being either an additional ligand or a structure-directing agent. These complexes are described herein, together with a complex involving CB8 and C6 obtained in the course of the study.

The first attempts at synthesizing uranyl complexes with linear, long chain dicarboxylic acids and cucurbiturils were aimed at checking the possibility to get rotaxanes based on included species different from the commonly used alkyldiammonium cations. A compound comprising two independent uranyl dinuclear complex units, one with three CB6 molecules and the other with one C102– dianion, [(UO2)2(CB6)3(H2O)6][(UO2)2(NO3)4(C10)]2·CB6·8H2O, has previously been obtained from reaction of a large excess of uranyl nitrate and sebacic acid with CB6 under hydrothermal conditions. Although a later result proved that azelaic acid could be included in CB6 to form the pseudorotaxane [(H2C9)(CB6)]·6H2O, no such complex with the terminal functional groups attached to uranyl could be obtained. In order to get a reaction medium displaying a higher diacid solubility, a series of experiments has been performed under hydrothermal conditions with addition of dimethylformamide (DMF) in the proportion of 1/7 to 1/3 in volume. In some experiments, alkali- or alkaline-earth metal ions were added in order to promote the dissolution of the cucurbituril. Although no rotaxane was obtained, the resulting complexes present interesting features, concerning both uranyl ion complexation by long chain dicarboxylic acids and the use of cucurbiturils in the synthesis of metal–organic assemblies. Some general trends are worth mentioning before a detailed description of the complexes. First, DMF is hydrolyzed under the conditions used to give dimethylamine (together with formic acid), which results in dimethylammonium ions being frequently present as counterions in the compounds. Formate ions are absent from the present complexes, but they are retained as ligands for uranyl ions in others, yet unpublished complexes. This DMF degradation occurring during the synthesis of metal–organic species is quite common and it has previously been documented. Second, several complexes involving alkaline-earth cations were obtained, but none with alkali cations, which seems to point to a larger affinity of cucurbiturils for the former in the present conditions. However, mixed uranyl/alkali metal cation complexes of CB6 were obtained in the absence of dicarboxylic acids, and they will be reported in due course. The yields of the syntheses are generally so low as to prevent chemical analysis; further, crystals are often mixed with amorphous powders. Although frequently plagued by the presence of disorder (particularly affecting the dicarboxylates and the counterions) or badly resolved solvent molecules, the structures of a series of nine complexes illustrating different aspects of the interactions between the various components present could be unambiguously determined. The complexes in which both the dicarboxylate and CB6 are bound to uranyl will be described first, then those in which the cucurbituril (CB6 or CB8) is uncomplexed, and finally those incorporating additional alkaline-earth metal ions bound to CB6.

elements.content: The three complexes pertaining to this series, [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(OH)2(C8)2(CB6)]·8H2O (1), [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(OH)2(C9)2(CB6)]·5H2O (2), and [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(OH)2(C9)2(CB6)]·8H2O (3), have similar formulas and closely related structures, notwithstanding the variation in the dicarboxylate chain length. The uranyl centers are arranged in centrosymmetric tetranuclear subunits, held together by two μ3-oxo and two μ2-hydroxo bridges (Figure ). The motif comprised of four uranyl ions held around two μ3-oxo bridges is often found in molecular compounds. In particular, it has been reported in association with CB6, the latter being either free or coordinated. It is also the building unit in the uranyl coordination polymers with C7, C8, and C9, including additional 4,4′-bipyridine or 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane ligands. The average U–O(μ3-O) bond length in complexes 1–3 is 2.27(5) Å (Table ), while the average value from the Cambridge Structural Database (CSD, Version 5.32) is 2.24(4) Å. The average U–O(μ2–OH) bond length of 2.35(4) Å in 1–3 matches that of 2.33(3) Å from the CSD. Atom U1 is further bound to one carbonyl group from CB6 (O11), with an average bond length of 2.541(8) Å, which is in the upper part of the range of values measured for uranyl–CB6 bonds, 2.337(6)–2.545(6) Å [mean value 2.40(5) Å]. Interestingly, the largest value measured up to now was for the previous tetranuclear complex of analogous geometry; it may be that the bulkiness of this group prevents a closer approach of the cation to the CB6 portal. Each tetranuclear unit is thus connected to two CB6 molecules, with the plane defined by the four metal atoms being roughly perpendicular to the mean plane defined by the six oxygen atoms of the CB6 portal [dihedral angles 82.72(3)–83.74(4)°]. Both U1 and U2 are in pentagonal bipyramidal environments, their equatorial girdle being completed by one bridging bidentate carboxylate in the case of U1 or one chelating and one bridging bidentate carboxylates in the case of U2. Each dicarboxylate ligand is thus bound to three metal ions, while each tetranuclear unit is bound to four dicarboxylates. The average U–O bond lengths of 2.49(2) Å for chelating and 2.38(2) Å for monodentate groups are unexceptional [average values from the CSD: 2.47(4) and 2.38(5) Å]. The mean equatorial planes around U1 and U2 are nearly parallel, with dihedral angles of 0.9(3)–3.5(3)° and the geometry around the μ3-oxo ions, although distorted from trigonal since the U1′–O5–U2 angle [139.5(3)–141.0(4)°] is larger than the other two angles [108.5(3)–111.6(2)°] due to the presence of the bridging carboxylate group, is nevertheless planar, with the sums of the three adjacent U–O5–U angles amounting to 359.8–360°. elements.content: Notwithstanding the similarity of the tetranuclear core/CB6 building unit in complexes 1–3, the polymeric arrangements display variations due to the flexibility of the dicarboxylate chain. In complex 1, the chain containing O7–O10 and that bound to U1 and containing O9′′ (Figure ), which are on either side of the CB6 ligand, are connected to a second tetranuclear unit. In complex 2, the two chains connecting the tetranuclear units are that containing O7–O10 and that bound to U2 and containing O10# and they are adjacent to one another. In both cases, [(UO2)4O2(OH)2(Cn)2]2– (n = 8 or 9) ribbons are formed, running along the [1 0 0] direction in 1 or the [0 1 1̅] direction in 2; a one-dimensional polymer of similar architecture is found in the uranyl complex of C92– including 4,4′-bipyridine ligands. In both compounds 1 and 2, [(UO2)4O2(OH)2(CB6)]2+ chains are formed in a direction transverse to that of the ribbons, which results in the formation of planar two-dimensional assemblies parallel to (0 0 1) in 1 (Figure ) or (1 1 1) in 2 (Figure ). It is notable that the sheets in 1, when viewed down their normal direction, display an overall packing arrangement similar to that defined by the sheets in 2 viewed edge-on and vice versa, with of course the directions in which the dicarboxylates extend and bridge the different units being different. The packings in 1 and 2 are thus very closely related to one another, with the flexibility of the alkyl chains being the source of the variation in connectivity. The topological analysis performed with the TOPOS software gives different total point symbols for the corresponding networks. The situation in 3 is different since no two dicarboxylates bound to one tetranuclear unit converge upon a single other such unit. Instead, carboxylate bridging ensures the formation of corrugated two-dimensional subunits parallel to the (1 0 1) plane, which are built from [(U4)4(C9)4] rings, where U4 stands for the tetranuclear unit. This arrangement is akin to that found in the uranyl complex with C82– and 4,4′-bipyridine ligands. Bridging of the layers in 3 by CB6 molecules gives rise to a three-dimensional framework (Figure ), which can also be viewed as resulting from the bridging of the [(UO2)4O2(OH)2(CB6)]2+ chains by dicarboxylate ligands. Apart from these differences in dimensionality and bonding geometry between the three complexes 1–3, it is interesting to note that all present the same overall feature of displaying layers of parallel CB6 molecules separated by layers (either really two-dimensional or formed by adjacent one-dimensional polymers) of general formula [(UO2)4O2(OH)2(Cn)2]2–. It thus appears that the tendency for uranyl ions to give planar or gently undulating ribbons or sheets matches with the propensity of CB6 to fit between them, as will be seen even more clearly in some of the subsequent complexes.

elements.content: Three complexes fall into this category, namely, [H2NMe2]2[(UO2)4O2(C6)3]·CB8·8H2O (4), [H2NMe2][(UO2)3O(OH)2(C7)(HC7)(H2O)0.5]·CB6·4H2O (5), and [H2NMe2]4[(UO2)4(C10)6]·CB6·H2O (6). Complex 4 appears as something of a curiosity since, while CB6 was used as a starting material, the final compound, obtained in very small quantity, contains CB8 instead. This phenomenon has previously been observed several times, one of them leading to an original CB8 complex with a uranyl sulfate polymer. The origin of CB8 in such cases remains uncertain, since it can either be present in the commercial CB6 sample used, or form in small quantity from CB6 under the conditions of the experiment. The basic subunit in 4 is once more the centrosymmetric bis(μ3-oxo)-bridged tetranuclear unit, but devoid of hydroxo ions this time (Figure ). One and a half C62– ligands are present in the asymmetric unit. The complete one (O5–O8) is bridging tridentate (both chelating and bridging) through one of its carboxylate groups and bridging bidentate through the other. The second ligand is chelating at both ends. The average U–O(μ3-O) bond length of 2.25(4) Å and the average U–(carboxylate) bond lengths of 2.50(6) and 2.38(7) Å for chelating and monodentate bonds, respectively, are unexceptional. The μ3-oxo ion O11 is in a planar environment, with the sum of the three U–O11–U angles [in the range 108.9(2)–131.1(2)°] amounting to 359.7°. The dihedral angle between the equatorial planes around U1 and U2 is 7.3(3)°. As in the previous cases, the charge of the complex is balanced by that of dimethylammonium ions, which are hydrogen bonded to carbonyl groups and lattice water molecules (Table ). The [(UO2)4O2(C6)3]2– subunit gives rise to a two-dimensional assembly parallel to (1 0 0), in which each tetranuclear group is bound to its six neighbors by six dicarboxylates, the basic motif being the [U4C6]3 ring, where U4 represents the tetranuclear unit (Figure ). These layers are separated by layers of CB8 molecules, the latter being at right angles to one another (Figure ), so as to permit the formation of CH···O(carbonyl) hydrogen bonds (H···O ≈ 2.4 Å), a frequent occurrence with cucurbiturils, which will not be further discussed here. Two points are worthy of note: again, the fit between the layer-forming ability of uranyl complexes on the one hand and of cucurbiturils on the other to give a crystalline mixed species is remarkable, and, second, the topology of the two-dimensional assembly is unprecedented in the family of uranyl complexes with dicarboxylates, and in particular with C62–, which shows the structure-directing role of CB8.

elements.content: Complex 5 is the only one in this series which involves C72–. The building unit in this case is not tetra-, but trinuclear, with the three crystallographically independent uranium atoms being bound to a central oxo ligand, O7 (Figure ). These trinuclear groups are bound to one another by double C7 bridges. U1 and U3 are both chelated by one carboxylate group, another carboxylate bridges U1 and U2, while the last carboxylate group is disordered and bound to U2 in either chelating or monodentate fashion (see ). Two bridging hydroxide groups (O8, O9) and a disordered water molecule (O18A) complete the coordination spheres. The average U–O(μ3-O) and U–O(μ2–OH) bond lengths of 2.25(3) and 2.35(3) Å and the average U–O(carboxylate) bond lengths of 2.49(2) and 2.400(7) Å for chelating and monodentate bonds, respectively, are in the usual ranges. The sum of the three U–O7–U angles [in the range 110.26(18)–137.4(2)°] is 359.8° and the uranyl equatorial planes are slightly tilted with respect to one another, with dihedral angles of ca. 15–26°. The trinuclear units are assembled into one-dimensional ribbons parallel to the [1 0 1̅] direction, which are positioned side-by-side to form layers parallel to the (0 1 0) plane (Figure ). These layers alternate along the b axis with sheets formed by the two crystallographically independent CB6 molecules (one of them hydrogen bonded to one dimethylammonium cation at each portal). In this case also, CB6 acts as a directing agent, inducing the formation of a uranyl–organic assembly of unprecedented geometry.

elements.content: Complex 6 is unusual in this series in that it involves isolated uranyl ions instead of polynuclear oligomers (although the uranyl/CB stoichiometry is still 4:1, as in compounds 1–4). Two crystallographically independent uranyl ions are chelated by three carboxylate groups each, provided by the three independent dicarboxylate anions, the uranium atoms being thus in hexagonal bipyramidal environments, with an average U–O bond length of 2.470(11) Å (Figure ). Doubly bridged centrosymmetric dimers are formed independently by U1 and U2 and their images by symmetry, and these rings are connected to one another by single dicarboxylates, thus giving a one-dimensional, helicoidal polymer extending in a direction parallel to [3 1 1̅]. The rings comprising U1 and U2 display different shapes, somewhat elliptical in the former case and much less regular in the latter due to the alkyl chains being buckled, with the consequence of a larger U···U separation for U1 [12.7214(10) Å] than for U2 [9.9509(7) Å], whereas the U1···U2 separation is even larger, at 12.8362(9) Å. This architecture is analogous to that in the complex with C62– including protonated 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane counterions, although only one type of ring is present in this case. No layer formation is observed and the CB6 molecules, as well as the disordered counterions, are located in the voids left by the quite intricate packing of chains (Figure ).

Among the three dicarboxylate ligands, two are partially disordered, with different bonding modes associated to each position (see ). In the first tetrametallic unit, U1 is either chelated by two carboxylate groups, both of them being also bridging and bound to U2 or its image by the inversion center, or one of these groups can be bridging bidentate. The two μ3-oxo ions complete the hexagonal or pentagonal bipyramidal environment of U1, while U2 is also bound to either a chelating carboxylate or a monodentate one and a water molecule (O23), its environment being in both cases pentagonal bipyramidal. Atoms U3 and U4 in the second unit are bound to a bridging tridentate carboxylate anion, a bridging bidentate one and, in the case of U4, a chelating one; both U3 and U4 are thus in pentagonal bipyramidal environments. The average U–O(μ3-O), U–O(chelating carboxylate), and U–O(monodentate carboxylate) bond lengths are 2.25(4), 2.53(5), and 2.41(9) Å. The tetranuclear units are connected in a quite intricate manner by curved dicarboxylates to give strongly corrugated layers parallel to the (0 1 1) plane (Figure ). The centrosymmetric CB6 molecule complexes one calcium ion at each portal, through two proximate carbonyl groups and with an average Ca–O bond length of 2.349(14) Å (Figure ). The first reported crystal structure of a cucurbituril was that of a calcium complex of CB6, and several other structures with calcium ions bound to two carbonyl groups are reported in the CSD, with an overall average Ca–O bond length of 2.42(5) Å. The calcium ion in 7 is further bound to four water molecules and one disordered DMF/water molecule located inside the cavity (see ). The association of the anionic uranyl–organic two-dimensional assembly and the cationic CB6 complex is particularly interesting. The latter forms columns along the a axis, around which the sinuous uranyl–organic sheets are spread out as wrinkled screens, thus isolating the columns from one another. The remarkable match between the channels defined by the polymeric species and the columns is likely a result of the structure-directing effect of the latter, but the ability of both species to associate in such a tight way is nevertheless noteworthy.

elements.content: Calcium ions are replaced by strontium ions in complexes 8 and 9, and the molecular calcium complex with CB6 is replaced by the [Sr2(CB6)(H2O) x (DMF) y ]4+ one-dimensional, columnar polymer (x = 7 and y = 3 in 8, x = 8 and y = 2 in 9), which extends along the a axis in both complexes (Figures –). Two strontium ions are bound at each portal of the centrosymmetric macrocycle, one to two carbonyl groups and the other to only one, each cation being thus bound to three carbonyl groups from two CB6 molecules, with an average Sr–O bond length of 2.67(9) Å (including both 8 and 9). Although several structures of strontium complexes of CB5 are reported in the CSD, few structures with CB6 are known, which are also columnar arrangements giving an average Sr–O bond length of 2.55(6) Å, lower than the present one. Water and DMF molecules, some of them disordered (see ) complete the eight-coordinate cation environment. Out of the three independent uranyl ions in 8, two (U1, U2) are part of a centrosymmetric tetranuclear unit and are bound to three carboxylate groups, one being chelating, one bridging tridentate and the other bridging bidentate, while the third uranium atom (U3) is chelated by three carboxylate ligands and forms [(UO2)2(C8)2] rings (Figure ). The average U–O(μ3-O), U–O(chelating carboxylate), and U–O(monodentate carboxylate) bond lengths are 2.262(16), 2.48(3), and 2.38(4) Å. The resulting assembly is two-dimensional and parallel to (1 0 0), but, although the dicarboxylate length is the same as in 7, the geometry is very different. The sheets in 7 are infinite in the direction of the column axis, while in 8 they extend in directions transversal to this axis, so that the sides of the channels are not defined by different sheets, but are part of the fabric of each sheet, the packing then providing the extension of the channels in the direction parallel to the column axis (Figure ). The overall packings in 7 and 8 are thus quite analogous, but they result from completely different topologies. Instead of being wrapped between sheets, the columns in 8 extend across stacked grids.

Conclusions

The series of nine compounds presented herein were obtained under hydrothermal conditions from a quite complex mixture of components: uranyl nitrate, CB6, long-chain alkyldicarboxylic acids, DMF (generating dimethylamine in situ), and alkaline-earth nitrates in some cases. As a result, the structures of the compounds are quite intricate and unpredictable. They display uranyl-dicarboxylate assemblies, with CB6 being either an additional ligand or a structure-directing agent. When present, alkaline-earth cations complexed to CB6 form columns which can also be seen as structure-directing units. Although uranyl bonding to CBn (n = 5-8) is now well documented, these molecules are much less efficient than carboxylates as uranyl ligands and carbonyl coordination is not always achieved when both ligands are simultaneously present; only compounds 1-3, among those reported herein, display such coordination. In particular, CB6 bonds preferentially to alkaline-earth metal ions, which is further illustration of the affinity of CBs for metals of group 2. Although they are also strong complexants of alkali metal ions, no such complex associated with uranyl-dicarboxylate assemblies could be obtained under the present conditions.

elements.content: Uranyl–dicarboxylate complexes involving the ligands used herein have been extensively studied by Cahill’s group, and it is notable that most structures of the present uranyl–organic subunits are quite different from those previously reported. There are however some trends which are consistently observed, the most obvious being the frequency of the formation of tetranuclear uranyl building units held around two μ3-oxo ions. There is some variation depending on the mode of attachment, monodentate, chelating, bridging bi- or tridentate, of the ligands to these units. Four types of tetranuclear units, denoted A–D, were recognized in the previous work, and those in the present compounds all correspond to form C (except for that associated to one of the positions of the disordered ligand in 7), that is, all uranium atoms are in pentagonal bipyramidal environments, with each of the two central ones sharing an edge with only one of the terminal atoms. However, there is the special feature in 1–3 of two bridges being μ2-hydroxo ions, a rather rare occurrence which was also observed in another complex involving uranyl bonding to CB6. Trinuclear, μ3-oxo-centered species are less common than tetranuclear ones, as shown by structures reported in the CSD, and a novel example has been obtained with complex 5. It is notable that the dicarboxylate chain length has only a moderate effect on the geometry of the assemblies, as exemplified by the closely related structures found for C82– and C92– in complexes 1–3 (although of differing dimensionality owing to the flexibility of the chains) or for the similar ones with C82– in 7 and C102– in 9. Conversely, the same dicarboxylate can give two different arrangements, as in 7 and 8, depending upon a slight modification of the other components of the system.

elements.content: The peculiar ability of the uranyl ion to organize its ligands in an equatorial plane is the origin of the propensity of this ion to give ribbon-like or two-dimensional, planar or corrugated polymeric assemblies. This tendency is apparent in the present complexes since the uranyl–dicarboxylate subunits (even when CB6 is present as an additional ligand) display such geometries in all cases. This trend is particularly interesting when these assemblies are associated with CBs since these large and barrel-shaped molecules often organize as columns or as sheets (being either parallel or at right angle to one another), and the present results show that these two kinds of assemblies readily associate. In all complexes 1–5, a stacking of inorganic and organic sheets can be seen, with coordination bonds between them in complexes 1–3; these layers are planar in compounds 4 and 5. However, the most remarkable arrangement is that consisting of winding uranyl–organic layers draped around columns of alkaline-earth complexes of CB6, as found in compounds 7 and 9: the cylindrical channels formed by adjoining corrugated sheets appear to be well suited to the encircling of the columnar CB6 complexes. In spite of analogous overall packings, compounds 7, 8, and 9 have different topologies: first, the columns are made of a stacking of molecular units with calcium ions in 7, while they are coordination polymers with strontium ions in 8 and 9; second, and more importantly, the uranyl–organic sheets are corrugated two-dimensional polymers extending along the column axis in 7 and 9, whereas, in 8, they are planar grids whose stacking defines channels occupied by the columns. Although the present study is limited to uranyl ion complexes, it is likely that analogous arrangements displaying inorganic layers isolated from one another by organic sheets or columns of CB molecules could be obtained with other metal ions of suitable coordination geometry. In this respect, the potential of CBs in the design of inorganic–organic layered materials with specific physical properties would need further investigation.
